cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.DC, cs.SI, cs.DS 

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as it focuses on caching at the network edge devices such as wireless caching stations (WCS) in the 5G network. It may also belong to cs.IT (Information Theory) as it discusses coded transmission schemes and leverages the broadcast advantage under the index coding framework. Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) as it deals with caching and updating content in multiple WCSs. It may also fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it considers the spatial-temporal diversity of content popularity and how it affects caching decisions. Finally, it could be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as it proposes a dynamic coloring approach to extend existing index coding-based schemes from a single-request scenario to a multiple-request scenario.
